A local privilege escalation vulnerability in Windows resides in the Windows Accessibility Infrastructure, managed by the Windows Configuration Manager at the kernel level.
The root cause is an incorrect permission assignment within the Windows Accessibility Infrastructure, specifically involving ATBroker.exe, which manages tools such as the On-Screen Keyboard and Narrator.
A standard user has write access to the HKCU registry path associated with accessibility configuration. ATBroker.exe copies values from this user-controlled location into HKLM paths that are ordinarily restricted to SYSTEM-level processes only.
When the workstation is locked and the Secure Desktop is activated, Windows spawns a second instance of ATBroker.exe running under SYSTEM privileges to manage accessibility tools on the secure session.
An attacker replaces the user-writable accessibility registry key with a registry symbolic link pointing to a privileged target, such as a Windows service's ImagePath value. Because ATBroker.exe running as SYSTEM does not validate whether the destination has been substituted, it transparently follows the link and writes the attacker-controlled value into the privileged location.
This results in the attacker gaining full NT AUTHORITY\SYSTEM privileges without requiring administrator credentials, UAC elevation, or any kernel exploit.
